1 (1) Has established a hunger task force that:
2 (i) Meets at least three times per academic year; and
3 (ii) Sets at least two goals with action plans;
4 (2) Has designated a staff member responsible for:
5 (i) Assisting students in enrolling in the Supplemental Nutrition
6 Assistance Program; or
7 (ii) Connecting students with available Supplemental Nutrition
8 Assistance Program outreach partners that can assist students in enrolling in the
9 Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program;
10 (3) Has designated a staff member responsible for informing students
11 participating in federal work–study programs that they are eligible for the Supplemental
12 Nutrition Assistance Program;
13 (4) (i) Provides options for students to utilize Supplemental Nutrition
14 Assistance Program benefits at campus retailers; or
15 (ii) Provides students with information on the names and locations
16 of off–campus retailers that accept Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program benefits;
17 (5) Participates in an awareness day campaign activity and plans at least
18 one campus awareness event during the National Hunger and Homelessness Awareness
19 Week;
20 (6) Provides at least one food pantry on campus, or enables students in
21 need to receive food through a separate, stigma–free arrangement;
22 (7) Develops and maintains a meal–sharing program that allows students
23 to donate their unused meal plan credits to be distributed to students in need for use in
24 campus dining halls or at an on–campus food pantry, if applicable;
25 (8) Conducts a standardized annual student survey on hunger and submits
26 the results to the Commission; and
27 (9) Submits an annual report detailing its efforts to address student
28 hunger to the Commission.
29 (b) The Commission shall designate as a hunger–free campus any campus of a
30 2–year public institution of higher education that meets all of the requirements for 4–year
31 public institutions of higher education or regional higher education centers identified in

